did.unittitle: Mount Vernon Seminary and College Nebraska Avenue Campus Collection
did.abstract: Having outgrown its M Street location, Mount Vernon Seminary moved to a 15.5-acre campus on Nebraska Avenue, NW, in 1917. School founder Elizabeth J. Somers died in 1924, and the Elizabeth Somers Chapel was dedicated on campus in 1925. Adelia Gates Hensley was headmistress until her death in 1923, when Jean Dean Cole became headmistress, a position she held until her death in 1939. It was under Ms. Cole's administration that MVS was divided into the preparatory and Junior College divisions. MVS celebrated the 50th anniversary of the seminary with a Golden Jubilee in 1925, and celebrated the Centenary in 1937 in observance of the 100th birthday of Mrs. Somers. In 1942, the United States Navy took over the Nebraska Avenue campus to use its facilities for the war effort.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Having outgrown its M Street location, Mount Vernon Seminary moved to a 15.5-acre campus on Nebraska Avenue, NW, in 1917. The buildings and layout of the campus were designed by New York architect Wesley S. Bessell and the campus was formally dedicated on November 5, 1917, Mrs. Somers' 80th birthday. Mrs. Somers died in 1924, and the Elizabeth Somers Chapel was dedicated on campus in 1925. Adelia Gates Hensley was headmistress until her death in 1923, when Jean Dean Cole became headmistress, a position she held until her death in 1939. It was under Ms. Cole's administration that MVS was divided into the preparatory and Junior College divisions. MVS celebrated the 50th anniversary of the seminary with a Golden Jubilee in 1925, and celebrated the Centenary in 1937 in observance of the 100th birthday of Mrs. Somers. In 1942, the United States Navy took over the Nebraska Avenue campus to use its facilities for the war effort. The complex is now home to the Department of Homeland Security.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains photographs, lantern slides, scrapbooks, programs, articles, menus, correspondence, and artifacts documenting the Mount Vernon Seminary and College students, faculty, and campus during the years 1917 through 1942, when the campus was located on Nebraska Avenue.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into four series: Images, Scrapbooks, Ephemera and documents, and Artifacts.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Collection acquired by GWU upon merger with Mount Vernon College. Collection transferred to Foggy Bottom campus in 2009.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into two subseries: Lantern Slides of Nebraska Avenue Campus and Facilities; and Photographs of Nebraska Avenue Campus, Students, and Staff.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs and glass lantern slides of the Mount Vernon Seminary and College Nebraska Avenue campus, students, and faculty. The slides, which date from 1917-1924, predominantly show exteriors and interiors of campus buildings and campus grounds. Most slides are captioned. The photographs, which date from 1917-1942, depict events, exteriors, and interiors, and also include student and faculty candids and portraits.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains scrapbooks of clippings mentioning Mount Vernon College and Seminary, as well as items and photographs from scrapbooks created by alumnae Florence Weaver Birch, Jean Syminton, Helen P. Andrus, Lillie Bowen Fairfax, and Marjorie Fitch Baker during their time as students at MVS. Scrapbooks date from 1923 to 1942.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains programs for commencements, plays, recitals, and menus from Mount Vernon College and Seminary from 1925 to 1941, as well as correspondence documenting preparations for the Golden Jubilee, the Centenary Celebration, and the creation of the Elizabeth Somers Chapel.
